[2]
Date: Mon 3 Nov 2008
Source: TimesOnLine [edited]
<http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article5073396.ece>


Investigators prepare to enter studio where drum maker died of anthrax
----------------------------------------------------------------------
An East London studio was in quarantine today [3 Nov 2008] as investigators
prepared to scour the workshop of a drum maker who died yesterday [2 Nov
2008] after inhaling anthrax. The man is thought to have contracted the
disease from imported animal hides, which he used to make bongo drums.
Health protection officials said that residents are not at risk from the
disease, which is not contagious.

This morning neighbours paid tribute to a generous man who taught music to
local children on the Morningside Estate in Hackney. Jules Pipe, the mayor
of Hackney, said today [3 Nov 2008]: "Our sympathies are with his family
and friends at this very sad time. The council is continuing to work very
closely with the Health Protection Agency (HPA). We want to reassure our
residents that inhalation of anthrax is extremely rare and does not pass
from person to person."

Officials from the Health Protection Agency will enter the workshop
tomorrow [4 Nov 2008], using protective equipment. The site is currently
under guard to ensure that no one enters the studio, but a spokeswoman for
the agency said that there was no risk to residents. Occupants of flats on
the same floor as the studio have been asked to stay away from the building
"for logistical reasons," she said.

Seven other people who had been in the room where the skins were prepared
were given antibiotics as a precautionary measure and the HPA said that
nobody else had developed any symptoms.

The investigation will focus on the animal hides that were used to make
bongo drums. It is thought likely that the anthrax spores may be traced to
hides imported from Africa, where the infection is endemic in animals. Any
hides found in the studio will be removed for testing at a government
laboratory at Porton Down, and results are not expected until next week.

Anthrax spores can be released when infected hides are scraped or otherwise
manipulated during the drum-making process, and breathing in these spores
can lead to infection. But there is very little risk from the finished
drums. "It is important to stress that it is the making of animal skin
drums that is the risk for coming into contact with anthrax rather than
playing or handling drums," Professor Nigel Lightfoot, the HPA's chief
adviser, said.

In Britain, the last similar case occurred in 2006, when a drum-maker from
Hawick in Scotland died after inhaling anthrax. A report concluded that he
picked up the illness from infected West African hides. Only one case has
ever been reported of anthrax being passed on by skin contact with a
finished bongo drum, and this was in Haiti in 1974. Last year [2007] a drum
maker in Connecticut (USA) contracted the more common cutaneous form of
anthrax from contact with untreated West African goat hides.

While all forms of anthrax can be fatal, the disease can be treated
effectively with antibiotics if detected early. Drum makers who work with
untreated hides and develop feverish illness or skin lesions are advised to
contact their GP (general practitioner).

[byline: Chris Smith]

