[4]
Date: Mon 3 Nov 2008
Source: UK Health Protection Agency (HPA) [edited]
<http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1225700805518?p=1204186170287>


Investigations following a death from anthrax
---------------------------------------------
Following the announcement of the death of a patient from inhalation
anthrax the Health Protection Agency (HPA) would like to offer its
condolences to the patient's family and friends.

As part of an investigation to identify where the anthrax originated from,
the HPA will be carrying out some testing at the patient's workshop in
Hackney tomorrow [4 Nov 2008]. This will involve a team from the agency who
will wear protective clothing and use a handling tent outside the property.
These are standard procedures when this sort of work is carried out, to
prevent the potential of any transfer of the bacteria.

Dr Brian McCloskey, director of the HPA in the London Region said, "We have
been working with Hackney Council and have spoken to all the residents of
this property. There is no risk to those living in this block of flats, or
the wider residents in the area. The patient's property is currently
secured and there is no-one living there. If this testing reveals the
presence of anthrax spores then we will speak to local residents about this
and specialist cleaning will be carried out to remove any trace of anthrax
from the property.

"We have also been following up any contacts of this patient who may have
been exposed to the anthrax spores by being in the same room when the
animal skins were being prepared and the drums were made. We have so far
given antibiotics to 8 people as a precautionary measure, and none of these
have developed any symptoms of anthrax. It is important to stress that it
is the making of animal skin drums that is the risk for coming into contact
with anthrax rather than playing or handling drums.

"We have stressed to all residents throughout this incident that there is
no risk to their health as a result of the case of anthrax, or the testing
that will be carried out. We are however keen to reiterate to all
individuals who make drums from imported animal skins that there is a risk
of coming into contact with anthrax and that they should ensure they are
aware of this and take precautions to protect themselves when making these
drums"

Notes to editors
----------------
1. There will be an opportunity for media to take photographs prior to the
testing starting on Tuesday [4 Nov 2008]. This will be at 8 am and after
this all media will be requested to leave so that the team can carry out
their work uninterrupted. If you would like to send a photographer then
please contact Emily Collins on 0207 759 2824.
2. Anthrax is a disease caused by spores that live in the environment. It
can cause a skin infection (cutaneous anthrax) or as in this case,
inhalation anthrax, when the spores are inhaled into the lungs. Inhalation
anthrax is very rare and is not passed from person to person. All
individuals who may have been exposed to anthrax spores during the making
of these drums have already been given antibiotics to prevent them from
becoming ill.
3. Despite the popularity of African drumming in the UK and elsewhere over
recent years, no cases of anthrax associated with these activities have
been reported. A single case of cutaneous (skin) anthrax associated with a
goat hide bongo drum purchased in Haiti occurred in 1974: this is the only
such case ever reported.
4. A case of inhalation anthrax occurred in 2006 in America in a man who
made drums from dried (but otherwise untreated) animal hides brought in
from West Africa. A recent case (in August 2006) also occurred in Scotland
in a man who made drums from imported animal hides.
5. Anthrax infections associated with the handling of untanned animal hides
are now extremely rare in the UK. Imported animal hides from countries
where anthrax is endemic in animals (for example, in Africa and Asia) pose
a higher risk for exposure than domestic (UK origin) hides.
6. Strict regulations are in place for the importation of animal hides.
These can be accessed at
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/int-trde/imports/iins/hide/bp5b.htm>
7. For further information about animal hide drums and anthrax please to go
<http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1195733752819?p=1191942145753>.

--
communicated by:
Health Protection Agency (HPA)

[Other reports:
<http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/health/3368306/Bongo-drummer-dies-of-anthrax.html>

<http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article5070999.ece>

Readers should note that although the patient had been under intense
medical care for a week, he still died from this disease. Once the symptoms
have started it is extremely hard to prevent human deaths from anthrax. So
far there is no information on how or why the patient's GP and the Homerton
University Hospital tumbled to the fact that he had pneumonic anthrax.
Someone was very alert and is to be commended.

Decontaminating such drum making establishments can be quite a challenge.
In spite of the press reports, only the deceased patient's workshop has
been sealed, not his flat (apartment). It would not be surprising if there
were a number of contaminated hides; they usually originate from street
markets in various African towns. While the HPA are not directly
responsible for checking professional and amateur drum making
establishments, they might consider encouraging local authorities to visit
other UK drum makers to check that their hides are healthy. Based on our
extensive field experience with various wildlife species of animals dead
from anthrax the Porton examinations should include PCR [polymerase chain
reaction] checks of the hides as culturing can and does, not infrequently,
come up with false negatives.

Whatever claims are made about controlling the entry of sun dried hides
from Africa and elsewhere it is clear that the present procedures need to
be revisited as well as the luggage inspection of UK tourists returning
from West Africa, and of West Africans visiting relatives in the UK. DEFRA
(UK Department for Environment, Food, and Rural Affairs) are responsible
for the control of imported hides. - Mod.MHJ]
